  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often from criminal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. \n\nIn the U.S., money laundering is prosecuted under various federal and state laws, including the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including:\n\n- Up to **20 years in federal prison** for each count.\n- **Fines** of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.\n- **Forfeiture** of assets involved in the laundering scheme.\n\nThe severity of the charges and penalties often depends on the amount of money involved, the nature of the underlying criminal activity, and whether the individual has prior convictions. Additionally, individuals or organizations involved in money laundering may face civil penalties, reputational damage, and other legal consequences.\n\nIf you are facing charges or have questions about money laundering laws, it is critical to consult a qualified attorney.",
